a) The Supply Officer/Inventory Committee prepare a consolidated Inventory Report to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records on a per account name basis and thereafter, reconcile with the accounting records to address the causes of variances;

b) The Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Property Unit and Accounting Office, prepare the Physical Inventory Plan, List of PPEs found at station, and henceforth, strictly comply with COA Circular No. 2020-006 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts presented in the financial statements; and

c) The Municipal Accountant record adjustments after reconciliation to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts and to strictly comply with the above-mentioned Circulars.

Set up the RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning of the year in compliance with section 20 of the Manual on the NGAS, Volume I and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers (SLs) in support of the RPT and SET Receivable balances so that reconciliation be made with the MTO;

Reconcile the Abstract of Real Property Tax Collections with the Municipal Treasurer based on Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card to update the list of delinquent taxpayers and to determine the actual balance of the Real Property Tax Receivables; and

Municipal Assessor is enjoined to furnish the complete and certified List of Taxpayers and taxes due in the beginning of the year as basis for set up.

We recommended that:
the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer exert diligent efforts to reconcile the Inventory accounts; and the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count at least twice a year, especially at year end, on all the inventory items to ensure accuracy and completeness of the amount recorded in the financial statements;
the Supply Officer to formulate policies, procedures and system on the inventory management of all inventories which include the regular updating of stock cards/records and reconciliation of their records to that of the Accounting Office, proper safe-keeping, order of disposal and other controls relative thereto;
Supply Officer to prepare a Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as his basis to prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the appropriate expense account and to compute the cost of supplies and materials issued and corresponding cost of the ending inventory account pursuant to IPSAS 12;
Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustment to the inventory account and reflect the appropriate expense account for the inventories that were already used, consumed or distributed based on the Summary of Supplies and Material Issued; and
Management to create Pharmacist position considering the huge amount allotted for the procurement of drugs and medicines, the volume of inventory accounts maintained by the Municipality and other inventory items received from DOH.

We recommended that management:
Require all officers and employees with outstanding cash advances to settle immediately after the purpose for which these were granted in conformity with COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445;
Cause the refund of any unused/unspent cash advances and/or no longer needed to the collecting officer to be receipted and shall be deposited to the LGU accounts;
Cause the withholding of salary of the officials and employees with outstanding cash advances specially those AOs mentioned in Item 5.1.d; and
To imposed Section 5.1 and 5.4 of CSC Memorandum Circular No. 23, s. 2019 after evaluating the status and reasons of non-liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management require the following:
Municipal Accountant ensures that all disbursements are duly supported with complete documents in accordance with Section4 (6) of PD No. 1445;
Concerned officials to fill up all necessary information in the purchase orders and other related documents correctly and consistently;
The focal person to post tarpaulin/streamer pursuant to Item 2.2.4 of COA Circular No. 2013-04;
The Supply Officer issue the Property Acknowledgement Receipt to all end users of the procured equipment; and
The Secretariat of the Bids and Award Committee to post the Request for Quotation and all awards in the PhilGEPS website and website of the Municipality in addition to posting at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the Municipality.

We have recommended that: 

The Municipal Accountant record cost of issuances and balance of inventories using the Weighted Average Method in accordance with PPSAS No. 12; 

The General Service Officer conduct inventory taking of supplies carried at stock at least every semester for reconciliation with the balance in the books.

We recommended that: 

the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management (LDRRM) Council implement DRRM programs and projects as planned to optimize the utilization of the LDRRM Fund of the municipality in order to strengthen its disaster preparedness and mitigation, and;

the Municipal Accountant disclose details of the unexpended LDRRMF in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that: 

a)	the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management (LDRRM) Council implement DRRM programs and projects as planned to optimize the utilization of the LDRRM Fund of the municipality in order to strengthen its disaster preparedness and mitigation, and;

b)	the Municipal Accountant disclose details of the unexpended LDRRMF in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

The Municipal Accountant ensure all expenses for the issuance of supplies are duly supported with the prescribed Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and reconciled with the Supply Ledger Cards to be maintained;

The Municipal Accountant record cost of issuances and balance of inventories using the Weighted Average Method in accordance with PPSAS No. 12;

The General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant maintain Supply Stock Cards and Supply Ledger Cards, respectively, in accordance with the NGAS Manual on LGUs; and

The General Service Officer conduct inventory taking of supplies carried at stock at least every semester for reconciliation with the balance in the books.

The Local Chief Executive create an Appraisal Committee to provide necessary fair market value of all municipal local road networks;

The Inventory Committee complete its inventory taking of municipal local road network, coordinate with the Appraisal Committee to provide the needed appraisal or fair market value, and report thereof shall be submitted immediately to the accounting department for appropriate recording; and

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer maintain subsidiary ledgers and property ledger cards, respectively, of all local road networks starting from the result of inventory taking by the Municipal Inventory Committee and the Appraisal Committee which shall be regularly updated.

We recommended that:
(a) the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management (LDRRM) Council implement DRRM programs and projects as planned to optimize the utilization of the LDRRM Fund of the municipality in order to strengthen its disaster preparedness and mitigation, and;
(b) the Municipal Accountant disclose details of the unexpended LDRRMF in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

